Parliament did not support an amendment to free Tymoshenko
The Ukrainian Parliament today rejected the proposal to repeal the amendment to the section of the Penal Code in which opposition leader Yulia Tymoshenko is sentenced.
The amendment would open the doors to the ex-prime minister&#39;s release, but parliamentarians rejected the proposal to reduce penalties for economic crimes in the second reading.
In October, Tymoshenko was sentenced to seven years in prison for allegedly signing an agreement with Russia disadvantageous to Ukraine on the purchase of natural gas.
The sentence is not yet final, the appeal court is required to review it in December.
Tymoshenko was convinced that it was a political revenge of the regime, and even in the West doubts have been raised about the impartiality of the court.
The proposal to withdraw paragraph 365 of the Penal Code with which the former prime minister was sentenced was supported by 147 deputies in the vote.
226 votes were required for its approval.
