Brand story:
The innovative IBM enters its second century of existence
If someone were looking for a term that would define IBM&#39;s strategy with great precision, the closest one would be &quot;long term.&quot;
For the general public, IBM is the symbol of a technological revolution, a company that is perceived as current and yet, a hundred years have passed since its founding.
The basis for this long-term character was laid by the first head of the firm, the visionary Thomas J. Watson Sr.
He has already coined the motto that many problems in the world can be solved if people are willing to think.
His motto &quot;Think!&quot; it became his seal, around which the life of the future giant will be built (it was also the title of an internal magazine that IBM began publishing in 1935).
Watson was also the foundation of a carefully crafted company culture.
&quot;For us, IBM means long-term thinking, continuous movement into the future.
IBM has survived and prospered for a hundred years for that reason, because it stayed true to its basic principles, but without fear of changes around it.
That has allowed us, during our first century, to transform technology, business and society.
We look forward to further prosperity in our second century, &quot;said current company CEO Samuel J. Palmisano on its anniversary.
A sophisticated system
Watson, already in the 1930s, took care of his employees as the businessman from Ba ela in the Czech Republic (IBM employees were among the first American workers to enjoy paid vacations, insurance, elegant uniforms and a sophisticated remuneration system that it rewarded the best inventors and salespeople.
The same long-term sophistication is maintained by IBM in customer relationships.
Right from the beginning the company knew how to discover talents (being one of the first companies in the world to end any type of discrimination, it could choose without problems).
In line with the anti-discrimination strategy is IBM&#39;s current plan, whereby Palmisano will be replaced next year by a woman: Virginia Rometty.
She has been with IBM for thirty years, where she has been head of sales, marketing and strategy.
In recent years, IBM has participated in so-called virtual meetings, online brainstorming, from which countless future strategies and innovations emerge.
It is not surprising that there are plenty of ideas, since almost half a million people work at the firm.
A reputable institution
The fixed position in the business provides the company with a strong internal and external image.
&quot;From the beginning, IBM maintained a concept of institution rather than technology company,&quot; says Harvard Business School professor economist and author of the IBM book Rosabeth Moss Kanter.
&quot;IBM is not a technology company, but a company that tries to solve business problems for technology users,&quot; says George Colony of the consultancy Forrester Research.
As the company itself says, there is a difference between going into business and directly creating a business.
IBM - or the &quot;Big Green&quot; - as it is known in the US familiarly because of its logo, has become in the last hundred years one of the largest companies in the world.
It is possibly the most versatile technology company (it develops both hardware and software, infrastructures and web hosting services within a wide range of services, ranging from servers to nanotechnology).
It holds the highest number of patents of all North American technology companies and five of its employees have received the Nobel Prize.
His inventions include the ATM, payment cards, swaps, barcodes, and floppy disks.
IBM will invoice this year 220 billion dollars. This year it has become the second technology firm by market capitalization (the first is Apple), when it first surpassed Microsoft in 1996.
Looking at the future
Not all products and innovations just satisfy the taste of customers and the moment (IBM did not bet on its own operating system, OS / 2, Prodigy online services or IBM PCjr computers).
&quot;If your business is based on moving forward, you cannot emotionally anchor yourself in the past,&quot; acknowledged Samuel J. Palmisano.
For this reason, IBM has no problem building its bases on other platforms (and equally, if they don&#39;t work, it abandons them).
And this differentiates it from the competition, Microsoft, which basically stays and always falls exclusively with Windows.
Future technology
In terms of sales, IBM is mainly dedicated to services, of which about a fifth are for software and another fifth for equipment.
Still, even in 1990, equipment accounted for more than half of the suppliers&#39; share.
As of 2000, IBM has sold underperforming assets for a total value of $ 15 billion. During the same period, it has invested 58 billion dollars in the purchase of future technology.
Investments have continued since 2008, when the modern global financial crisis first struck.
IBM acts according to the premises of its first boss, Thomas J. Watson, who during the great economic crisis of 29 increased investments.
It seems that until now the IBM company has managed to weather the crisis.
The value of IBM shares since the beginning of 2008 has grown stratospheric up to 120%, the net profit of the company has not stopped increasing.
IBM&#39;s motto is to change everything except its value.
So it can be expected that when the next crisis comes, this flexible giant will hold out.
IBM history: from cheese slicer to space flight
The company IBM (International Business Machines) was founded in New York one hundred years ago, being its original name Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
The name IBM was adopted as early as 1924 - originally it was a brand used in the Canadian and South American branches.
The foundation that gave rise to the birth of IBM stems from the merger of four companies dating back to the 1880s.
He had inventions such as the famous &quot;time clock&quot;, which allows controlling the entry and exit of employees.
The architect of the new company was businessman Charles Ranlett Flint, who until 1930 also chaired its supervisory board.
Flint hired the boss of a competing company, Thomas J. Watson, to help him run the company.
The new leader overshadowed the founder of IBM (Watson&#39;s ideas remain the firm foundation on which corporate identity and culture are built).
Watson ran the company until 1952.
IBM, as the name implies, began with the production and sale of all kinds of business gadgets, from meat and cheese cutters to cash registers.
During the first four years that Watson led the company, the turnover doubled by 9 million dollars and the great expansion of the company began throughout the continents.
Watson was so crucial to the company that, after almost forty years in the boss&#39;s chair, he was replaced by his son, Thomas Watson Junior.
Under his direction, IBM began work on the development of artificial intelligence and developed the first programming language.
In the 1960s, IBM staff and computers helped NASA guide the flights into space (to Mercury, Saturn and in 1969 the famous flight to the Moon).
Meanwhile, in 1964 IBM developed the first generation of computers, the IBM System / 360 series.
The classic &quot;fish&quot;, which established the standard for computers of that time, hit the market under the name IBM 5150 in 1981.
Twenty years later, IBM sold its computer production to the Chinese company Lenovo, which, for its part, acquired the consulting part of the Pricewaterhouse Coopers company and began to offer comprehensive advice and high-value-added services.
The strategy that IBM has paid for these last three years is the Smarter Planet concept, that is, &quot;a smarter planet.&quot;
Its aim is to make a more rational use of technology, although the areas have not yet been planned and the circumstances have not been improved, for example, in relation to transport and city administration.
For the retail sector, IBM recently introduced the &quot;Smart Commerce&quot; platform that enables retailers to manage the entire business cycle.
IBM has a long history in this country.
Already in 1932 it opened a branch in the then Czechoslovakia, the first country to have it in Central and Eastern Europe.
Here today, IBM ČR also operates the strategic outsourcing center in Brno.
The headquarters for Central and Eastern Europe is in Prague. Also here is a world-famous research team working with speech recognition.
