How travel prices have evolved since 1989
Until 1989 there were only five authorized state travel agencies in Czechoslovakia at that time: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
The travel agencies of that time sold in most cases trips only to the socialist bloc, since travel to the West was very restricted.
Czech tourists therefore went on vacation to the beaches of the GDR (German Democratic Republic), the Soviet Union (Sochi in Crimea on the Black Sea), Bulgaria and Romania (both on the Black Sea) and Hungary ( Balaton).
A positive exception was the period between 1962 and 1972, when it was possible to travel to Yugoslavia, however, afterwards the Yugoslav regime leaned west and Czech tourist travel was then quite restricted.
A great paradox of socialism was the fact that the citizens of the socialist bloc (that is, also the Czechoslovaks) were not allowed to travel freely and individually even in the socialist countries.
If a citizen wanted to travel individually, for example, to Poland or the Soviet Union, he needed an invitation letter, if not, individual travel was not possible.
Travel agencies in those days also offered trips to the West, but one had to stand in line with a sleeping bag and spend the whole night like that, or have &quot;good acquaintances&quot; in the agency.
Still all was not won.
The so-called &quot;promise of change&quot; that was the condition for travel to the West was not granted to &quot;politically unreliable people&quot;, who thus could not travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely convertible currency and, without a guarantee of exchange, it was not possible to obtain the resources (the western currency) to travel to the West.
The vast majority of Czechs spent their holidays in their own country, so there were a large number of cottages and summer houses, which the Czechs bought. This custom still persists.
The Czech way of traveling has undergone a real revolution since 1989.
While until 1989 it was the ultimate vacation in the GDR or Bulgaria for us, last year the Czechs made 4.5 million vacation trips to countries around the world.
It is a great paradox, of which we are no longer aware, the fact that the currently favorite destination, Croatia, until 1989 could not travel freely, because it was part of the Yugoslavia at that time.
In the early 1990s, a visa waiver was imposed for travel to neighboring Western European states, causing a huge wave of short-term visits, especially to Vienna or Germany.
Czechoslovaks, for a long time, did not look fed up with excursions to the West, everyone wanted to see it at least for a moment.
For example, in Paris groups of Czechs slept in the parks in tents, since our income at that time did not allow us to pay for a hotel or pension.
A typical characteristic of the Czechs of that time was to take food with them (preserves, sausages, etc.) to save money.
Another important moment was the introduction of the convertibility of the Czech crown, so that our tourists could finally, after decades, freely buy Western currency.
Our standard of living increased and with it average wages, which around 1997 caused an increase in the demand for travel.
With the increased demand for travel, agencies began, starting in 1997 regularly, to prepare trips using charter connections, which made travel prices incredibly lower compared to the past, thanks to the possibility to obtain discounts for the volume of passengers.
At the end of the 90s of the last century, Czechs were already traveling visa-free to almost all developed countries except the USA, which further simplified our travels.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolutionary tourism happened already in 2000, when the first direct flight from the Czech Republic to an exotic country was organized, thanks to a huge demand, and went to Thailand.
Since that year, direct charter flights depart every year with Czech tourists to distant and hot countries. This winter there will be direct flights from the Czech Republic to 12 exotic destinations.
Exotic countries are currently visited by about 100,000 Czechs a year.
Another interesting moment of this time, symbolizing our post-revolutionary development, came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the US eliminated visas for Czech tourists, making our country among the most developed countries in the world.
In 2008 Czechs, for the first time in their history, spent more than half of their holidays abroad (50.3%) and for the first time in their history, more than 15 thousand crowns were spent on trips abroad Czechs per head, including expenses on the site of stay.
Ordinary General Assembly called to elect the president, who could end up in a standstill again.
For almost five months, Czech football has been without a president and it is likely that Ivan Hašek&#39;s successor as President of the Czech Football Federation (FAČR) will not be known even after the convening of the next Extraordinary General Assembly that will take place this Thursday. in Nymburk.
In fact, an agreement has not yet been reached on the voting rules to follow.
