The most beautiful pools in Europe
Jump to the blue
by Julia Stanek
Pools from an incredible perspective, sumptuous baths in Budapest: Whoever visits Europe can experience its blue wonder, and, after a visit to the city or a walk, rest their tired legs in bubbling baths.
A book shows where the best well-being is in the water.
When Iris Meder went on a research trip over the past year and a half, there was something she couldn&#39;t miss in her luggage, a swimsuit.
Lying on her back in the water, she gazed at the artistic dome overhead, swam to the marble angels that awaited her at the edge of the pool, and marveled at the meticulously restored modernist indoor pool.
He liked the bathroom, taking note in his notebook at the time of all the interesting details about the style and history of the building.
The architectural historian Meder explored more than 200 pools in this way and presents them in her recent book &quot;Badefreuden&quot;: the indoor pools in Munich, the historic bathing palaces in the Black Forest, the &quot;concrete constructions&quot; in Taunus.
He made his &quot;trip through the most extraordinary baths in Central Europe&quot; through 13 countries: In addition to Germany, Austria and Switzerland, he visited places in Italy, France, the Czech Republic, Slovakia, Slovenia, Hungary, Romania, Poland, and a city respectively in Luxembourg, Serbia and Croatia.
This 46-year-old German is a true fan of bathroom culture.
It doesn&#39;t want to have anything to do with sport, says Meder, only the water is different.
It only bothers him that bathroom fans have to settle for blue tiles and the stench of chlorine, while joggers can breathe in the mesmerizing smell of spruce forests or hear the joyous chirps of birds in the park.
&quot;One day I wondered why swimming pools always have to be so ugly,&quot; says this Vienna resident.
&quot;I started collecting nice pools.&quot;
The surface of the water duplicates the architecture.
The splash in the pool and the ethereal oils of the sauna. The wellness factor in pools is so great because all the senses are catered for, according to Meder.
