&quot;On the one hand it is transparent, on the other it reflects the beauty of the entire building.&quot;
Everything is optically doubled: the high vaults, the colored tiles, the trampolines.
The small-format photo book &quot;Badefreuden&quot; provides on 190 pages very interesting facts about the architecture and art history in the historical oases of well-being, but, mainly, it makes you want to jump into the blue.
Meder, the swimming pool collector, discovers the outstanding specimens in her research in Hungary.
Along with the magnificent medicinal baths such as the 100-year-old Széchenyi bath in Budapest, there are waters with nitrates in a unique karst cavity (cavity baths in Miskolc-Tapolca), as well as some thermal baths, whose pools are of alkaline waters and they are in a bottle-shaped building (Városi Termálfürdö in Jászberény).
Many outdoor pools in Switzerland and Austria offer spectacular views: As the whole city casts its eyes on Zurich&#39;s indoor pool, you can gaze out at Arlberb, covered in snow, from the outdoor swimming pool in St. Anton, and: In the Turkish bath there is a window from which you can watch the practice on the ski slopes.
Perhaps the most extraordinary design awaits customers in Längenfeld: Ötztal&#39;s Water Cathedral looks like a UFO that has just landed in the Alps.
Steam rises from three open springs in winter, while the Ötztal Mountains rise into the sky in the background.
Alhambra in the Black Forest
Meder, the pool collector, didn&#39;t get the smell of chlorine in every pool.
Many thermal baths smell of sulfur, in the Árpád baths in Békescsaba, Hungary, the stench of diesel is so strong that people believe they have reached a sanitary bath.
The smell comes from the medicinal waters that contain bicarbonate and alkali and whose silt sticks to the skin when entering the pool, an enjoyment of well-being in a special way.
Iris Meder was also disappointed in one place in her search for beautiful bathing spots, when she wanted to visit outdoor pools and sun baths in the Luhatschowitz Czech bath, she came across a blocked ground.
Architect Duan Jurkovic&#39;s 1902 bathroom was closed.
When Meder looked through the crumbling windows of the red, white, and yellow modernist building, he saw weeds grow between the tiles.
The decadence countered in a charming pool in the Black Forest: the Thermal Palace in Bad Wildbald.
These baths have three construction phases behind them; Not only can you discover neo-Romanesque elements from the time of its construction in 1844, but also an Alhambra-style Arab hall, added in 1900.
Since its painstaking modernization in 1995, the Thermal Palace is the favorite bath of the pool collector, Iris Meder, and not only because it is a native of the Black Forest.
