The construction is considered to date a contemporary landmark of architecture.
He made the architect so well known that he also built the Austrian pavilion at the next world exhibition.
With its legendary four-cylinder tower for MBW plus the adjacent flattened building in Munich, it became internationally known.
Its pavilion, designed as a temporary building for exhibitions, was erected after the universal exhibition in the Schweizer Garten next to the Vienna South Station, was renovated in 1962 and inside a museum of the 20th century was inaugurated, it was called the &quot;20th house &quot;.
The building was adequate but lacked adequate space and technology for a museum; no wall to hang art, no good atmosphere.
Despite this it was used until contemporary art in Vienna had a new home.
The building has been empty since 2001 and is increasingly decaying.
Currently, the architect Adolf Krischanitz renovated the pavilion, now calling it &quot;house 21&quot; and it will be used in the future as a museum of contemporary art.
On Tuesday afternoon the belvedere museum, to which the house belongs, was inaugurated with the first exhibition, a stroke of luck in a way.
Agnes Husslein-Arco, the new director of the Austrian Belvedere Gallery since 2007, made a fresh start.
Husslein-Arco, a doctor in art history with a considerable career, among other things, an ice figure skater in her youth, later at Sotheby&#39;s, the Guggenheim museum, and founding director of the Salzburg Museum of Modern Art, carried out the renovations with the insistence of politicians and protectors of the monuments, provided public funds and private sponsors and established their use.
With the exception of contemporary art, the works of the sculptor Fritz Wotruba of the homonymous foundation are exhibited, there should be a cafeteria and a bookstore and an office building should also be built.
Tight control, low budget
Krischanitz was the best choice to do it.
Not only because he sensitively reformed the secession of Joseph Olbrichs in Vienna, expanded it and was awarded the competition, but also because he studied with Schwanzwer at the Technical University of Vienna and the pavilion was for him an &quot;important and immense place&quot;, in which he contemplated &quot;almost every weekend&quot; the exhibitions.
He knew the project and the problem of the building, which disappeared with his transfer to Vienna in his change of use with generosity and ease.
In the current renovations there are big problems, the building was &quot;a drain on energy&quot;, said Krischanitz.
The profile of the windows of the glass façade was changed, an insulating glass reinforced with fiberglass was installed and the glass roof was replaced by a special safety glass.
The thermal bridges and steel girders were reinforced or replaced and the asbestos roofs were rehabilitated.
Two basements were employed for the new use, a light panel lowered between the house and the street provides the illumination, a bridge serves to enter the almost new building, but still the Schwanzer pavilion.
The original exterior doors remain, the house is painted in antique mahogany tones and protected against rust.
And the movie theater is exactly as it was before.
And all this with strict control by the monuments office and a low budget.
&quot;Often I had to find material that was good, cheap and also liked by the monument protection office,&quot; says Krischanitz, noting a rough floor in the basement.
Despite all the pressures, problems, and renovations, the building remains flexible and lightweight.
The pavilion &quot;that came from Brussels&quot; has been difficult, Krischanitz said recently, a typical &quot;chance appearance in the history of the city.&quot;
Such an architecture is &quot;always in the wrong place&quot; and that is why he wanted to &quot;awaken the right conscience.&quot;
In this case, house 21 is not in the wrong place, there has been an urban windfall. The totally new and planned &quot;Central Station Quarter&quot;, with homes and offices, is adjacent to the Schweizer Garten.
