They look for alternatives in the cities
Ecologists attribute the problems of the cities to the migration of certain protected rooks from the countryside; chemical applications in agriculture visibly destroy traditional living spaces.
Hunting, growing buildings and falling trees that host them make life difficult for birds.
The rooks are protected.
There are large colonies with more than 600 breeding pairs in Soest, Westphalia, among others, in the northwest, among others in Jever, Diepholz and Achim in Bremen, as well as in Leer.
