Critics have called hunting the animals using bird traps and killing with sticks especially brutal.
&quot;Driving them out and driving them away in the normal way does nothing,&quot; said Werner Klöver, urban planner and landscaper from Leer.
Shooting nests with water or throwing trees are often unintended consequences, says Manfred Kaiser, an environmental expert from Lahr, Baden-Württemberg.
&quot;Animals wander off, large colonies divide and distribute them elsewhere.&quot;
Driving them away is only imaginable as an exception in hospitals, nursing homes or schools.
&quot;We must live with them, we no longer catch them.&quot;
Without the surroundings, the problem in cities is not solved, says Wolfgang Kellner, Mayor of Leer.
