Filmed before the age of Pixar, the iPod, or the iPhone, there is something strangely prescient about The Lost Interview, as Jobs assesses what he sees other companies doing right and wrong, and offers his own insight into the future of computing.
It&#39;s one thing to read posthumous reviews of Jobs&#39; career, but there is something crude and inspiring about the Jobs we see here, the eager dreamer on the brink of greatness.
He has a vision of how things can and should be.
Not long after explaining everything in detail here, he went and did it.
A quick recap of seven notable sequences from The Lost Interview:
On how he learned to run a business:
&quot;Throughout the years in the business, I always asked,&quot; Why do you do things? &quot; and the answers they invariably give you are, &quot;Oh, that&#39;s just the way it&#39;s done.&quot;
