How to detect a lie
A glance at the latest headlines tells us how serious and pervasive deception and lying are in everyday life.
Republican presidential candidate Herman Cain is busy trading sexual harassment allegations with several women; each party accuses the other of lying.
Administrators at Pennsylvania State University have been charged with perjury for allegedly hiding reports that a retired soccer coach was sexually assaulting children.
Last week, French President Nicolas Sarkozy was &quot;caught&quot; with an open microphone claiming to US President Barack Obama that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu is a liar.
Lying has destroyed careers and convulsed countries.
New York congressman and Internet exhibitionist Anthony Weiner made a fool of himself with his denials quickly refuted by irrefutable evidence.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards has been charged with campaign finance violations related to covering up an extramarital affair.
And again, no one who lived through it will ever forget the media circus unleashed by President Bill Clinton when he lied during his second term about his sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
Legends about cheating on school and college exams are widespread.
There have been cases where teachers have given test answers to students in order to be better seen in their performance evaluations.
Mentors who should be teaching otherwise are sending the message that lying and cheating are acceptable.
How much deception do we find ourselves?
On any given day, studies show that you can be lied to anywhere from 10 to 200 times.
That&#39;s for sure, many of those lies are white lies.
Another study showed that strangers lied three times in the first 10 minutes of meeting.
Detecting lies, or &quot;locating lies&quot;, is an essential skill that we must all acquire, for both personal and professional reasons.
Far from being a board game similar to, for example, Charada, where the objective is to exclaim: &quot;I have you&quot;, the detection of deception is a serious branch of knowledge based on scientific data obtained during the last six decades in prestigious universities that conducted in-depth research projects, especially in psychology and physiology.
One of the results of the research is that the old myths about lying have been dispelled.
Liars do look eye to eye.
They don&#39;t always stutter, stammer, blush, or fidget.
Nor can it be concluded that liars are difficult to detect or unmask.
A trained lie detector can get to the truth by learning about statement structure, microfacial expressions, question formation, and timing.
I spent several years probing scientific discoveries about deception in the vast and ever-emerging body of knowledge, and it was clear that deception detection is a modern technique that is easy to learn and helps navigate our complex world - especially if its responsibilities Professionals include recruiting, interviewing, or managing negotiations.
Good liars have the ability to read others well, making them feel at ease, managing their own emotions, and intuitively feeling how others perceive them.
We know from research that extroverts lie more than introverts, that men tell more &quot;self-oriented lies&quot;, while women tell more &quot;other-oriented&quot; lies - usually to protect someone&#39;s feelings - that married people lie to their partners less frequently than unmarried people (but the lies they often tell tend to be &quot;huge&quot;).
We also know that if you are perceived as a wrongdoer, others will feel less guilty about lying to you.
How do you know if someone is lying?
First, observe the habitual behavior of the subject.
This is called &quot;creating a baseline.&quot;
Helps provide benchmarks to measure changes later.
Observe the subject&#39;s posture, laughter, and vocal characteristic.
You better know if someone normally taps their feet all the time so that you don&#39;t make unfair accusations when you see their feet tapping in the middle of the meeting.
Next, look for deceptive, verbal and non-verbal groups of behavior.
View these behavioral groups as red flags, not proof of deception.
Cheating people may freeze their upper body when trying to recall their story, point their feet toward the door, lean toward an exit, change their posture significantly, or exhibit &quot;post-interview relief&quot; - that exaggerated sigh of relief and change of posture once all the tough questions are over.
Interrogators often falsely pretend the interview is over just to seek that post-interview relief.
Also pay attention to the vocabulary of the subject.
Scott Peterson really screwed up and used the past tense while claiming that his murdered wife was alive, launching a nationwide search for her.
Cheaters may also use distancing language: &quot;I did not have sex with that woman ... Miss Lewinsky&quot; or repeat a difficult question in its entirety.
The most common verbal cues are subtle.
Someone can use a lot of &quot;restrictive language&quot; when answering a difficult question: &quot;Well ... to tell the truth ... as far as I know ... as far as I know.&quot;
This makes the answer a perception rather than a fact and is often a red flag.
There is no magic bullet for detecting lies, but developing deception skills is possible.
These skills will improve anyone&#39;s chances to avoid being victimized by scam artists in their professional and personal lives.
