The new Italian government will be formed on Wednesday
The designated prime minister, Mario Monti, will meet tomorrow with the president of Italy to present the new government that will face a crisis that has placed that country on the brink of economic disaster
Italian Prime Minister-designate Mario Monti will meet with the President of Italy on Wednesday to present the new government that will face a crisis that has brought Italy to the brink of economic disaster and put the entire eurozone in jeopardy.
A statement from the presidential palace announced that Monti, appointed on Sunday, will meet with President Giorgio Napolitano on Wednesday to confirm that he can form a government.
He is expected to present a cabinet made up mostly of technocrats, although it is unclear when the new executive will take office.
Monti said he will present to the president the results of his talks with political parties in his attempt to form a government.
&quot;I want to confirm my absolute confidence in the ability of our country to overcome this difficult phase,&quot; the former European commissioner told reporters.
Monti did not explicitly say that he will be able to form a government, but the tone of his comments indicated that the obstacles have been overcome.
The &quot;framework is now well delineated,&quot; he added.
Monti has completed the process of forming a government in less than three days, much less than normal, as Italy battles a political and financial crisis that has driven its debt costs to unsustainable levels.
The new administration led by former European Commissioner Monti must pass a tough austerity package demanded by European leaders to regain battered confidence in Italy.
Underscoring the pressure on Monti to hurry, market instability pushed the yield on Italian 10-year BTP bonds above 7 percent, the level at which Greece and Ireland were forced to bail out.
Emma Marcegaglia, leader of the Italian employers&#39; association Confindustria, told the press after meeting with Monti: &quot;We said we would support this government a lot.&quot;
We believe that this Government is the last chance for Italy to emerge from this emergency situation.
Monti&#39;s chances of success were boosted considerably by the PDL party&#39;s backing of Silvio Berlusconi, who the crisis forced to resign on Saturday.
&quot;We believe that Professor Monti&#39;s efforts are destined to have a good result,&quot; Angelino Alfano, secretary of the center-right party, told reporters.
The support of the PDL, Italy&#39;s largest party, is significant because so far many of its members had opposed the technocratic majority government that Monti is forming.
Parliamentary support
The new Monti government must have strong parliamentary support to implement what will likely be unpopular austerity reforms.
Any blockage or delay in your efforts could provoke a new and devastating attack on the financial markets.
The Italian association of foreign banks added to the pressure by warning that a failure of Monti would be a disaster.
Monti began his consultations with political parties, unions and business groups, as well as youth and women&#39;s organizations, on Monday.
He will end his round of meetings on Tuesday night.
Monti was appointed on Sunday by Napolitano, who has enabled an extremely rapid transition in response to the crisis.
After a brief respite at the end of last week, when it became clear that Berlusconi would resign, Italian debt costs have now returned to critical levels amid uncertainty over whether the new prime minister will succeed.
Bailing out Italy, with a public debt of 1.8 trillion euros, would be too much for the current financial defenses of the eurozone.
Monti has said his government should last until the next elections, scheduled for 2013, despite widespread predictions that politicians will only give him time to implement the reforms before advancing the elections.
Monti has said that he would like to include politicians in his cabinet, but the major parties insist that it should be made up only of technicians, an indication of his reservations about a process forced by financial pressure.
Political sources pointed out that mutual distrust and disagreements between parties are complicating the attempt to include political figures.
