Since November, Mexico has presided over the G20, a group made up of the world&#39;s most powerful emerging and developed countries, and has in force with the South American country, since January of this year, an agreement to exchange tax information in order to avoid double taxation.
The Uruguayan government has tried in recent years to speed up the conclusion of fiscal exchange agreements in order to get out of the &quot;gray list&quot; of the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD), made up of countries that did not implement all the international standards of cooperation in tax matters.
