The municipal contest on the 16 doors reopens the debate on the role of Collserola in Barcelona
In the mid-1980s, at the height of the now defunct Metropolitan Corporation of Barcelona (CMB), this Administration printed some promotional posters for Collserola.
The brochure defined the mountain as the great park of metropolitan Barcelona.
Moreover, it was accompanied by a comparison, in figures, with New York&#39;s Central Park.
With the death of the CMB in 1987, the park was once again located, in the imagination of many, as the upper limit of Barcelona, being the Catalan capital one of the few that are not oriented in the north-south axis but up (mountain ) -down (sea).
The classification of Collserola as a natural park results in this idea.
The reference was no longer Central Park but Yellowstone, with the wild boars in the role of the Yogi bear.
In these it was until, in September, the city council called a mega-competition composed of 16 contests for as many access doors to Collserola.
A door refers to the idea of a park, without a doubt.
Either that or someone intends to put doors to the field.
The question comes out alone: Collserola, park or mountain?
The competition, both for its purely organizational aspect and for what it means to reflect on the city, is the topic of conversation among all Barcelona architects.
It is almost a recurring theme to draw upon when two members of this ancient chosen caste recognize each other in an elevator.
And this fact gives rise, precisely, to one of the few coincidences between what three Barcelona architects think, and university professors, who have presented themselves.
Miguel Roldán, Daniel Mòdol and Marta Bayona: the contest is timely.
For Roldán, after addressing the coastline &quot;it is necessary&quot; to discuss &quot;the mountain front&quot;, since Ildefons Cerdà&#39;s speech, that of the green apples, has not been carried out.
&quot;It should be assumed that the largest park in Barcelona is the beach.
Among other things for its great accessibility.
Collserola is more complex &quot;, says the architect for whom the title of&quot; Collserola gates &quot;contains a&quot; lexical trap &quot;: one should not think of them&quot; as the entrances to a park, but rather the delimitation of areas where it is necessary to act &quot;.
Mòdol, like Roldán and Bayona with experience in the urban world, qualifies the proposal as an &quot;intellectual challenge&quot; with &quot;some dangers&quot;.
Dangers derived from the &quot;uncertainty that it is today to project public space&quot; after the experience lived in the 80s and that &quot;his swan song&quot; had in the Forum area.
The first fear is the very delimitation of borders on where it can be built.
&quot;To limit something is to fix the next step&quot;, that is, its overstepping.
&quot;You have to think about new urban planning instruments, because the current ones [in reference to the General Metropolitan Plan (PGM)] can give rise to real disasters.&quot;
Closer to the question, Mòdol believes that, simplifying, the Collserola slope of the valley &quot;can be understood as a park, that of Barcelona cannot&quot;, for a merely topographical question.
Mòdol recalls that there is already a job done by the Patronat de Collserola that &quot;should not fall on deaf ears&quot;, although he appreciates the opportunity that the city council offers his union to intervene in this project &quot;from the first moment&quot;.
And even more, he understands that the mountain&#39;s proximity to the city is the safe conduct that allows architects to enter the debate, but he &quot;doubts&quot; whether it is this technical profile that should lead the multidisciplinary teams (&quot;quite a success&quot; , points out) that have had to be created: &quot;We architects should only be a tool.&quot;
Bayona insinuates that the answer to the question that gives title to this piece is complex, because the bases of the contest lack a global vision of Collserola: &quot;16 transversal competitions have been called,&quot; he says, &quot;in the mountain-sea sense, but there is no a longitudinal reading that sees and understands the area as a whole &quot;.
This causes, at least in your case, that you have chosen to participate in the 16 contests.
Otherwise, a project for one of the doors may clash in program and definition with that of the architect next door.
In his opinion, yes, the city council should guarantee that the strip immediately above the Ronda de Dalt should provide, in its entirety, an area of facilities that would make a smooth transition between the city and the green.
