After 72 days of arraigo, the legal representative of the Casino Red granted the pardon to the brother of the mayor of Monterrey of the process that was followed for alleged blackmail
After spending 72 days in prison, Manuel Jonás Larrazábal will be released after the legal representative of Casino Red granted him a pardon before the Second Criminal District Court, which is following a process for blackmail against the brother of the mayor of Monterrey.
After the attack on the Casino Royale, the owner of the Casino Red, Sergio Gil García, made public a series of photographs and videos in which Manuel Jonás allegedly demanded the payment of an economic fee so that the Monterrey city council would allow the clandestine operation of the betting house.
After the public complaint, the State Attorney&#39;s Office opened a criminal proceeding against the brother of the PAN mayor and on September 2 he was detained and held for 30 days.
After four hours before the Agent of the Public Ministry 3 in Property Crimes, he was transferred to the House of Arraigo 1, located in the Old Quarter of the State capital.
In that place he remained for the following 49 days when a second arrest warrant was issued after the agent of the Public Ministry dismissed the crimes of bribery and organized crime.
On October 19, he was transferred to the Cadereyta prison for allegedly blackmailing the owners of the Red Casino with a million and a half pesos; however, he only remained in the medium security prison for a few hours as there were death threats against him.
The authorities allowed him to continue the trial in the municipal cells of San Nicolás de los Garza.
On October 25, an arrest warrant was issued by the secretary of the Second Criminal District Court, Jorge Yánez, who said that after almost two months of investigations, sufficient evidence was verified to determine the guilt of Jonás, such as the collection of 1.5 million of pesos to the representatives of the bookmaker in exchange for allowing the operation of the same.
This Monday, the legal representative of Casino Red, Víctor Aldo García Gómez, went before the judge José Luis Pecina to request a pardon for the brother of the royal mayor; so that in the next few hours he could regain his freedom.
During the legal proceedings, the agent of the Public Ministry attached to the Court, Ramiro Arias, questioned García Gómez if the damage had been repaired and who of the partners of the betting house was the one who granted the pardon, although the lawyer tried to reserve the Name.
Based on the file 197/2011 legal pardon is granted to Jonás Larrazábal and henceforth no claim may be filed regarding the process that was followed; In addition, no reparation for damage or punishment will be required.
After the hearing with the legal representative of the bookmaker, around 3:50 p.m., the immediate release of Larrazabal Bretón was ordered.
The court clerk, Jorge Yánez, went to the San Nicolás de los Garza municipality jail to notify Jonás that he has been legally pardoned and his file will be archived.
It will also notify you of the immediate release order issued by the judge.
Secretary Dionisio Pérez Jácome gives details of the plane crash in which the Secretary of the Interior, Francisco Blake, and seven other people lost his life
The Ministry of Communications and Transportation (SCT) reported that the results of the accident in which the Secretary of the Interior, Francisco Blake Mora, and seven other people lost his life, indicate that the helicopter directly impacted on the ground in complete integrity structural, without the pilot being able to attempt a forced landing.
During a press conference, Dionisio Pérez Jácome, Secretary of Communications and Transportation, mentioned that before the aircraft took off, the pilot verified that the weather conditions were suitable for flying.
&quot;The elements that seem to indicate that the unit had several contacts with the ground, the blades had contact with trees 25 meters away where the unit lost the fuselage.&quot;
He also reported that the unit was designed for 19 people, so it had the necessary requirements to transport personnel.
In addition, he said that in the investigations carried out in the impact zone, the appearance of pieces on the ground was not reported.
&quot;In a search they reported that there are no parts or components of the ship in another place, the impact was structurally present.
&quot;The design of the helicopter was for 19 passengers, it had adequate requirements to transport the passengers.
The terrain presents a slope of seven degrees at a 30 degree incline.
For the moment, the secretary assured that it is a priority to have the results possible beforehand; however, the investigation can last several months, it could even reach a year.
For his part, Gilberto López Meyer, general director of Airports and Auxiliary Services, assured that at the time of impact, the helicopter of the Presidential General Staff was operating at cruising speed and that this happened on an ascending soft ground.
&quot;This information strengthens the hypothesis of a normal cruise operation at the time of impact,&quot; he said.
At the press conference, the head of the SCT, Pérez Jácome, listed six relevant elements in the investigation:
Visual flight:
In accordance with aeronautical regulations, the flight was carried out under visual flight rules, this implies that the crew must have visibility during the flight and on the ground.
Weather conditions:
The reports in the AICM located suitable conditions for takeoff, as the aircraft advanced towards the border area between the DF and the State of Mexico, layers of cloud cover appeared at low altitude.
Selected routes:
It is likely that due to the cloudy conditions, the crew sought an area of lower elevation and greater visibility towards the Cuernavaca valley.
Impact location.
The impact coordinates and the last record of the radar aircraft coincide, probably before the impact there was no loss of control or alteration in the flight path.
Dispersion of aircraft wreckage in a reduced area:
The information available so far allows us to assume that the impact occurred in a straight and sideways trajectory.
The dispersion pattern of the aircraft debris allows us to assume that the helicopter hit the ground in conditions of structural integrity.
No evidence of fire or explosion detected:
At the scene of the accident, evidence of some kind of explosion or fire has not been revealed in the remains of the ship.
The latest results of the investigation indicate that he may have had multiple contacts with the field.
During the field work, parts of the aircraft have been found at an elevation of 9,200 feet above mean sea level, the terrain presents a slope that ranges from seven degrees to 30 degrees of inclination.
The photographs show the sequence in which it was predictably dismantled along that route.
The information provides elements that seem to indicate that the helicopter may have had multiple impacts on the ground.
After a meticulous search in an area wider than the cordoned off site, around the accident, no scattered pieces of the aircraft have been found, which strengthens the presumption that the impact occurred in conditions of structural integrity.
MSS Announces Protocol to Find Obesity Gene
Social Security conducts research to discover the obesity gene in children and young people; is supported by specialists from the IPN
The Mexican Institute of Social Security (IMSS) announced that it is conducting an investigation to discover the obesity gene in children and young people, called the &#39;Genetics of childhood and adolescent obesity&#39; protocol, which will allow for markers associated with overweight.
In a statement, the head of the Medical Research Unit in Biochemistry of the Hospital de Especialidades of the Centro Médico Nacional Siglo XXI, Miguel Cruz López, explained that a multidisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers was integrated.
This team is supported by specialists and graduate students from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Center for Research and Advanced Studies (Cinvestav) of the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
In the research, the population is invited to participate, whether or not it is entitled, to go to the participating sports units of the IMSS in the Valley of Mexico, where the tests are carried out on minors, every Saturday from 8:00 a.m. hours.
He stressed that the protocol began in the Cuauhtémoc Sports Unit (State of Mexico Poniente) and that since October 8, the activity is carried out in the Nezahualcóyolt Sports Unit (East Mexico State).
Once the goal of reuniting 500 or 600 minors is met, the study will continue at the Independencia Sports Unit (south of the Federal District) and finally at the Morelos Sports Unit (north of the Federal District).
He explained that the purpose of this research is to know the components and the importance of genetics with respect to the development of obesity and to identify risk factors in Mexican children and young people to prevent the appearance of chronic degenerative diseases.
When celebrating World Diabetes Day on November 14, he specified that the objective is to bring together three thousand children and young people between six and 14 years of age, with the consent and supervision of their parents, for the application of specific questionnaires on food .
They will also be asked about physical activity and family history of diseases, in order to avoid risk factors that trigger conditions such as diabetes or kidney failure.
He explained that on Saturdays, anthropometric measurements (weight, height, waist circumference), blood pressure measurement, determination of glucose, triglycerides, cholesterol and insulin and genetic measurements are applied to all participants (it seeks to identify genes that are associated to childhood obesity).
Cruz López pointed out that this investigation is due to the concern of health professionals about the alarming weight gain in minors.
&#39;The 1999 and 2006 health surveys indicated that in just six years there was an increase, in the case of boys, of 77 percent in obesity, and of girls of 47 percent; in terms of overweight, a dramatic rise was also observed &#39;, highlighted the IMSS specialist.
He indicated that the justification for the search for markers is based on the fact that the country&#39;s population differs from others due to its genetic history.
He reported that on average, the Mexican has 65 percent American Indian heritage, 30 percent European and five percent African and this condition is reflected in the genes that are associated with diabetes and excess weight.
He explained that in general, the genetics of obesity translates into the inability to burn the excess energy that we consume (calories) and that is stored in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit for the participants is the comprehensive evaluation of the children, which makes it possible to detect whether they are overweight or obese.
Even, he said, the presence of dark-colored folds (acanthosis) on the neck and forearm, which indicates the probability that he suffers from metabolic alterations and even prediabetes.
The information is handled confidentially, the doctors deliver it in writing to the parents, who are explained each of the measurements and the changes in the lifestyle that they must make to prevent diseases.
Cruz López explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic conditions: sedentary lifestyle, which is the lack of daily physical activity, spending most of the day sitting in front of the television and using means of transport instead of walking distances short.
It is also due to the high caloric intake, that is, the higher consumption of sugary drinks, carbohydrates (tamales, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) with high fat and protein content, and the genetics that are analyzed in this protocol.
UNAM asphalt would avoid potholes
Rafael Herrera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry at UNAM, develops polymer-modified asphalt to produce a mixture with better performance, regardless of environmental and temperature conditions.
If the signals sent by the pavement were heeded, it would not be necessary to repair nearly 200 thousand potholes each rainy season in the Metropolitan Area of the Valley of Mexico, warned Rafael Herrera Nájera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) of the UNAM, who assured that if the process of construction and maintenance of an asphalt pavement is adequate, potholes could be reduced in quantity or even eliminated completely.
In his conference A technological opinion on potholes, given within the framework of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory under his charge develops polymer-modified asphalt to produce a mixture with characteristics similar to those of asphalt, but with a greater mechanical resistance, both at high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera estimated that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places where the climate is extremely hot, such as some cities in the north of the country, to improve its performance and, therefore, the formation of potholes.
He explained that asphalt, the heaviest part of oil, is a set of hydrocarbon molecules, some with high molecular weight, called asphaltenes, and others with low molecular weight, called maltenes, which together give the pavement its characteristic viscoelastic behavior.
The viscoelastic behavior of asphalt consists in that at high temperatures, close to 180 degrees, it behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees Celsius its viscosity is very high and at 50 degrees Celsius it presents an almost solid state, while at very low temperatures, the asphalt becomes brittle, he added.
This means that in the streets the resistance of the asphalt is not uniform, but it is modified during the day according to the environmental and temperature conditions, the chemical engineering specialist warned.
The FQ researcher observed that the streets of Mexico City are mostly covered by flexible pavement, which is made up of six layers of materials, of which the last three involve asphalt.
Among the most superficial layers is the asphalt layer, made up of small stones bathed in asphalt and then compacted.
Each of the pebbles that make up the folder, he pointed out, is bathed in asphalt.
When the vehicles travel and efforts are generated, it allows the forces to spread very well on the pavement.
If it were modified asphalt, they would spread even better, said the chemical engineer.
On top of the asphalt mat, he added, a last layer called the tread mat is placed, which is made of a fine stone material, that is, a sand that is also bathed in asphalt.
As it is the layer that will be in contact with the vehicle tires, it must have more mechanical strength than the asphalt mat and provide friction on the road.
As it is the part of the pavement that is going to receive and diffuse the efforts, the rolling mat also requires having the appropriate thickness and the material from which it is made must be taken care of.
Climate, especially humidity and temperature variations, are also a very important factor to consider, especially water, he said, because it considerably affects the performance of the asphalt mat.
When the ground gets wet, the water diffuses into the interior of the mat and is difficult to get out, this causes a softening of all the layers of the pavement and, therefore, the formation of potholes.
In the process of forming a pothole, he said, the first to wear out is the bearing film and only afterwards is the asphalt layer affected, but the damage does not occur instantaneously, it is a process that should be attended to at the first signs with adequate maintenance schedules.
The also member of the National System of Investigators explained that the vehicular load is another important factor in the formation of potholes and, therefore, the thickness of each of the layers of the pavement must always be in relation to the vehicular load and guarantee that they are Comply, to avoid frequent potholes.
Rafael Herrera warned that there is still much to research and work on asphalt, for example, asphalt emulsions, which in other countries are already on the market and allow potholes to be repaired easily and without the need to use high temperatures.
