This was the work of the Caleño who identified the body of Alfonso Cano
A lofoscopist from Cali went down in history as the man who confirmed the death of &quot;Alfonso Cano.&quot;
The work of these officials is key.
On November 4, a lofoscopist from the CTI of Cali went down in history as the man who confirmed the identity of the top FARC chief: &quot;Alfonso Cano&quot;, by checking his fingerprints.
Of the seven lofoscopists who work in the CTI section, that week it was the turn of &quot;availability&quot; to Eliazar González, a man from Puerto Tejada who has been working in the judicial investigation area for 21 years.
At the beginning of his career, González worked in municipalities of Chocó, where many times he had to go into the jungle for more than five days to reach the place where the bodies were to be identified.
In 2000 he moved to the capital of Valle and, after taking the corresponding courses, he specialized in lofoscopy, which is the study of friction skin, that is, of the palms of the hands and feet.
The week of the operation against alias Alfonso Cano, Eliazar was warned to wear clothes for at least three days.
Something great awaited him.
On Friday night he left for Cauca in a helicopter from Palmira.
He knew that he had to identify two bodies and that one of them was suspected to be the man who led the oldest guerrilla in the world, so they asked him to carry the ten-digit card of Guillermo León Sáenz (his real name).
However, when he arrived with the investigation team at the site where the body was found, he did not recognize it by its physical appearance, as it was very different from what he had seen in the media.
He was beardless, dressed like a local peasant, without glasses, and much thinner.
But the footprints don&#39;t lie.
Accompanied by a Galtonian magnifying glass, ink, a transplanter, and a flashlight, Eliazar compared the fingerprints on the corpse with those on the card.
His eye did not fail him: it was &quot;Alfonso Cano.&quot;
That same night, the man from Puerto Tejada was in charge of confirming to the Minister of Defense, Juan Carlos Pinzón, that he was the top FARC chief.
In search of the footprint
For a fingerprint specialist from the Sijín de Cali, the recognition that President Juan Manuel Santos made to Eliazar González at the press conference for the operation against &quot;Cano&quot; is very significant.
Many people do not know our work.
Fingerprinting is an exact science, with no margin for error, which can be key in solving crimes.
Apart from identifying corpses, lofoscopists support investigations for crimes such as theft and homicide and confirm the identity of those captured.
When caught, many criminals present false IDs or do not have papers.
We take their fingerprints and look them up in the database.
The investigator said that, in a theft case, he had to remove a piece of wall from a house, because in that place the thief had supported his hand to remove a safe full of jewels and money.
&quot;The walls are difficult because they are not suitable surfaces to take a fingerprint, but in that case we were able to obtain the print of the entire hand and identify the criminal, who had participated in different thefts,&quot; he recalled.
Fingerprints can also rule out or reaffirm suspects in homicide cases.
They recently found a dead man, with bottles of liquor around him.
Through the investigation it was determined that a relative could be a suspect in the crime and, indeed, a fingerprint on the bottle matched.
Although this does not guarantee that he was the murderer, it does locate him at the crime scene.
A fingerprint specialist from the CTI explained that on the objects &quot;the prints are taken with chemical or physical reagents.&quot;
When they appear, a transplanter or tape is used to lift them.
After this, the impressions are sent to the Asif, which is the criminal database, or to the Registrar&#39;s Office.
&quot;The problem is that there are still many undocumented Colombians,&quot; said the CTI expert.
He clarified that not everything is as it is shown in the CSI television program.
Just as not everything that glitters is gold, not everything that is touched becomes a mark.
However, if it can be used, if the respective comparison is made.
The &quot;indignant&quot; challenge authorities in New York
Hundreds of protesters gathered outside Zuccotti Square to camp.
A large part complied with the eviction order and moved to a nearby park.
Members of the Occupy Wall Street movement challenged the New York authorities on Tuesday by trying to re-enter, under the protection of a court order, the Manhattan square from where they were evicted at dawn and by trying to occupy another park in the big Apple.
Hundreds of protesters crowded in front of Zuccotti Square, where they wanted to access thanks to a court order that allows the &quot;indignant&quot; to go back to camp in the place, while another part of the movement responded to the eviction by occupying a park further north of the city , where there have been new arrests.
&quot;Our idea is that if the court does not allow us to go back to camp in the square, we will settle somewhere else and continue the legal battle to return to Zuccotti, as well as through sit-ins and peaceful demonstrations,&quot; said one of the spokesmen of the movement &quot;Occupy Wall Street&quot;, Mark Bray.
Bray explained that the response of the &quot;outraged&quot; to the eviction of their camp dictated personally by the mayor of New York, Michael Bloomberg, reached the courts, where Judge Lucy Billings issued an order that prohibited the forced evacuation of the place and allowed protesters to stay camped.
In addition, the &quot;indignant&quot; proceeded to occupy a new park located at the confluence of central Canal Street and Sixth Avenue, very close to the entrance to the Holland Tunnel, which connects New York and New Jersey, and owned by the parish. of Trinity Church.
For at least an hour they managed to occupy the place, but then the police came and proceeded to arrest some of the protesters, although Bray could not confirm the specific figure, while he assured Efe that he saw several journalists who were also handcuffed.
The organization assures that there are several hundred people who had settled at that point, where a delegation of religious leaders has already moved in support of the members of the movement and that they have tried to mediate with the Police.
Meanwhile, Zuccotti Square -which is a privately owned compound- is still closed pending the holding of a judicial hearing scheduled for this Tuesday in which the legality of the evacuation this morning must be analyzed.
Some of the protesters displaced there carried and distributed copies of that court order at this time and even handed them over to the agents who were guarding the square, which caused &quot;some small clashes,&quot; said Bray, who denounced that some officers struck at protesters.
The court order prohibits authorities from evicting Occupy Wall Street members or enforcing &quot;laws that were issued after the occupation began or prohibiting protesters from re-entering the park with stores or other properties they previously used.&quot;
Mayor Bloomberg indicated to the press that, due to that court order, the city had suspended the reopening of the space to the public and protesters, alerting them, however, that local laws do not allow them to reopen with retail stores. campaign and sleeping bags.
The councilor personally defended the eviction carried out at dawn from Zuccotti Square, an operation in which around 200 arrests were made and which was decided because the protesters were &quot;breaking the law.&quot;
Bloomberg explained that he gave the order to evacuate the square because it was becoming &quot;a place where people did not come to protest, but to violate the laws and, in some cases, to harm other people&quot;, since &quot;some businesses had received threats&quot; and neighbors feared &quot;for their quality of life.&quot;
&quot;The eviction this morning was disgusting and shows that deep down Bloomberg is more interested in preserving financial interests than those of American workers,&quot; added the spokesman for the movement, who accused the mayor of &quot;disrespecting the freedom of expression&quot;.
Those responsible for &quot;Occupy Wall Street&quot; also indicated that they plan to organize &quot;big actions&quot; for Thursday in collaboration with community organizations and unions, to commemorate the two months that the protests last, which began on September 17.
