Japan is reborn after the earthquake
GDP grows by 1.5% thanks to domestic consumption and ends the spiral of falls that began in March
Since last March, the Japanese economy was paralyzed, still convalescing from the devastating earthquake that turned into a nuclear crisis, the worst catastrophe that the Japanese country suffered since World War II.
The first estimates of the Government of Tokyo put the material losses in 300,000 million dollars, a blow that, despite the difficult world context, seems to have lessened.
After three consecutive quarters of falls, the Gross Domestic Product data between July and September served to turn the page, definitely: GDP increased by 1.5% compared to the previous quarter and by 6% in an annualized rate.
The one registered in the second quarter - for the Japanese, the fiscal year begins in March 2012 - also represents the highest growth rate since the period from January to March 2010.
The recovery is explained, in part, by the rise in the purchase of machinery to restore the areas devastated by the earthquake and the subsequent tsunami.
In fact, companies increased their investments by 1.1%, compared to the 0.9% decrease in capital expenditures observed from January to March, the first setback after six months of uninterrupted increases.
However, the true boost of the Japanese economy is not based exclusively on the Keynesian impulse that invites us to take advantage of the crises to reinforce - or rebuild - the infrastructures, to use the deficiencies to grow from zero.
Japan has awakened, above all, thanks to the evolution of domestic consumption, which currently represents 60% of Japanese GDP.
This variable climbed 1%, driven by the increase in spending on vehicles, travel and leisure activities.
The stigma of the yen
Tokyo has been entrusted to the domestic market, when the yen - Japan&#39;s currency - has become one of the &quot;safe havens&quot; chosen by investors fleeing the debt crisis in the euro zone and the murky forecasts of the US. ., a privilege that weighs heavily on the accounts of exporting companies.
With a stronger currency, products are more expensive abroad, a serious setback for a country whose economic waterline is determined by the health of large technology groups.
Toyota or Sony, for example, attributed their weak results between July and September to the price of the yen.
As the markets continue their siege to the peripheral countries of the EU, the government of Yoshihiko Noda does not lower its guard.
&quot;We must be attentive to the risks that persist, such as the deterioration of some foreign economies, the impact of the floods in Thailand and the rapid appreciation of the yen,&quot; said Secretary of State for Economic Policy Motohisa Furukawa yesterday.
And indeed, the prospects are not encouraging.
The Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD) specified that most member countries showed clearer signs of economic slowdown in September.
The indicator that anticipates the turning points in the world economy highlighted that the major powers are holding back.
Since it fell four tenths to 100.4 points, compared to 100.8 in August.
The euro zone, even, was below the average, which is at the level 100, falling eight tenths to 99.13 points.
Athens feeds doubts again
Papadimos says the adjustments will be approved, but the Conservatives will not sign any written commitments
