On Tuesday, the yen rose to reach levels close to the all-time highs that led to the intervention of the Japanese authorities on October 31.
That day, Tokyo sold yen for dollars in droves to lower the value of the Japanese currency, which had just hit a new record since 1945 compared to the US currency.
But the yen has been rising gradually since then, driven by purchases from investors who consider it a &quot;safe haven&quot; in these uncertain times of global economic slowdown and debt crisis in Europe.
The dollar was quoted again on Tuesday below 77 yen and the euro has fallen below the symbolic bar of 105 yen, reaching levels close to those that caused the last intervention.
Before the financial crisis of 2008-2009, the dollar was trading at around 120 yen and the euro at over 160 yen.
This explosion of the Japanese currency harms the archipelago&#39;s exports, since it makes Made in Japan products more expensive and reduces the value of the income obtained abroad by Japanese companies when they convert them to the national currency.
&quot;Japan is struggling to rebuild&quot; after the earthquake and tsunami of March 11, which devastated the Tohoku region (northeast), said Noda, who fears that the rise in the yen will cut the weak recovery in the bud.
The third world economic power has recovered growth in the third quarter (1.5% compared to the previous quarter), for the first time in a year, thanks to an increase in exports and consumption of households affected by the catastrophe.
But the Prime Minister believes that the high level of the yen did not reflect &quot;Japan&#39;s economic foundations&quot;.
Finance Minister Jun Azumi has asked the Bank of Japan (BoJ), which opened a two-day meeting of its Monetary Policy Council on Tuesday, to take all possible measures to weaken the yen.
However, the Deputy Governor of the institution, Hirohide Yamaguchi, warned that the BoJ had already taken &quot;the appropriate measures&quot;, implying that greater monetary flexibility should not be expected on Wednesday.
During its last meeting at the end of October, the issuing institute increased its purchases of Treasury Bills by five trillion yen (47 billion euros), raising the threshold of funds to 55 trillion yen (519 billion euros). dedicated to the acquisition of various financial securities to flood the market with liquidity.
