Energetic politics:
facts must be worth more than dogmas
If there is an issue that cannot be dealt with in the light of short-term considerations or simply thinking about emotions, it is energy policy.
The availability and cost of electricity directly influence the purchasing power and competitiveness of companies.
It is fitting that an electoral meeting is the time to reflect on such issues and the place of nuclear energy.
The debate will only be useful if you study all the economic, social and environmental consequences of the proposed options.
The French must base their opinion on objective facts, on rational data.
Now that we are 7,000 million people on the planet, demographic evolution will mean a doubling of electricity demand before 2050, unless a huge part of the world&#39;s population is deprived of a vital element.
At the same time, it will be necessary to alleviate the growing scarcity of fossil resources to continue producing electricity continuously, without forgetting the urgent need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions to fight climate change, an issue that has disappeared from the debate. ecological.
The Fukushima accident does not modify any of these parameters.
That is why Germany stands alone in its decision to renounce nuclear energy.
This is not the case neither in Belgium, which subjects theirs to the need to find a source capable of replacing it, nor in Switzerland, which only aims to build state-of-the-art plants.
On the other hand, Great Britain, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India and Brazil, to name a few examples, are determinedly moving forward with their projects.
The United States, for its part, after Fukushima decided to add a unit to its park, resuming the construction of a power plant that was interrupted after the Three Mile Island accident.
If the German model, based on renewable energies, is sometimes presented as an example, reality goes against such a discourse.
The election of Berlin will mean an increase in the price of electricity, a greater dependence on energy due to the increased need for imported gas, in particular from Russia, an increase in CO2 emissions from the construction of gas and coal plants.
In a few months, the detrimental effects will be noticeable.
The case of Denmark should be considered.
European champion in the wind sector, from which it obtains 30% of its electricity, it is also one of the major users of coal and gas due to the intermittent wind; for this reason, its CO2 emissions and the price of its electricity are, respectively, 65% and 50% higher than the European average.
On the contrary, thanks to the constancy of our energy policy, our neighbors pay an electricity bill 40% higher than that of French households.
While in a globalized economy the cost of energy is a key factor in competitiveness and a guarantee of the maintenance of industrial utility in the national territory, French companies benefit from the cheapest electricity in Europe.
For this reason, any significant reduction in nuclear energy would mean a sharp rise in the price of electricity, which would make the wonderful statements about the reindustrialization of our country and the defense of our purchasing power unrealistic.
This is a price that the vast majority of French people refuse to pay and, in fact, do not express opposition in principle to this type of energy, polls show.
Let us remember that the energy policy of our country has lost building an industrial sector with 125,000 director jobs and 410,000 indirect jobs.
Broadly export-oriented, it encompasses a galaxy of SMEs specialized in international markets and capable of creating non-relocatable jobs.
If France decided to abandon nuclear power, it would mean the sacrifice of a large part of these SMEs and the loss of the 6,000 million euros per year in French exports of nuclear equipment and services.
What electrician would commission an EPR designed to run for sixty years, when its manufacturer is expected to collapse?
To solve the nuclear energy equation, one must admit that there is no miraculous source of electricity production, just as there is no diabolical source.
Areva&#39;s development of solutions with low CO2 emissions, nuclear and renewable, demonstrates the complementary nature of energy sources.
In the case of nuclear energy, it is essential to maintain the highest level of safety.
In France, we have a Safety Authority that exercises strict and transparent control over both the existing plants and the construction of Flamanville.
Our highly professional teams are also obsessed with safety.
In half a century, the nuclear sector has suffered three serious accidents.
Only one, Three Mile Island, was produced under normal operating conditions; It did not cause consequences for people or the environment.
At Chernobyl, the accident was due to reactor design and inexcusable human failures.
In Fukushima, some people seem to forget that the accident was caused by two natural disasters of an unprecedented scope, which killed tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear industry will learn from this accident, just as it did from the previous two.
Thanks to these advances and to a cooperation between the safety authorities, and the French and German operators and constructors, the EPR presents a design capable of withstanding such phenomena.
While it is being studied by all the electrical players who want to build a plant, the interruption of its construction in Flamanville would be a great gift for the competitors of Areva and EDF, since it would leave them free to assume leadership in the inevitable development of the nuclear sector.
It is essential and legitimate to seek the best energy options for our country, but it would be irresponsible to let emotion, dogmas and partisan maneuvers dominate a debate so important to the economic, social and financial situation of our country.
Immigration, a burden or an opportunity for the economy?
The immigration policy applied by Nicolas Sarkozy has been criticized from various points of view: the saturation of the police, judicial and administrative services subjected to the policy of figures, the compatibility of this policy with the self-proclaimed status of &quot;country of rights Humans &quot;from France.
More recently, it is the administrative harassment of foreign students that has made headlines, with the Interior Minister (see the May 23 newspaper Libération) proclaiming in the past that France &quot;does not need foreign talent, laborers or waiters.&quot;
However, it is rarely analyzed from an economic point of view.
The point is that, on this issue, there is a lot of consensus between the left and the right.
In the case of the right, Jacques Chirac set the course by stating in 1976 that &quot;900,000 unemployed should not be a problem for a country with nearly two million migrant workers,&quot; while on the left, the tone was set by Michel Rocard explaining that France &quot;cannot take care of all the misery in the world&quot; in 1990.
The only difference, the degree of generosity
In 2005, both the left and the right shared the fear of invasion of the national territory by a multitude of Polish plumbers.
On both sides, immigrants are seen as a burden on the French economy and society.
The only difference is in the degree of generosity with which they act towards immigrants.
In his program, François Hollande limits himself to including banalities, indicating that co-development will allow solving the &quot;problem of migration&quot;.
This idea of immigration as a burden, a problem, may be electorally profitable, but economically it is very expensive.
As the economists Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron point out in a recent work summarizing the latest knowledge about immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 pp.) , there is a broad consensus among specialists on the positive impact of migratory flows on economic growth, wages and employment in countries that receive immigrants.
Limiting immigration weakens growth and hurts employment.
Fears related to the impact of immigrants are based on the idea that immigrants can replace national workers, particularly the low-skilled, by pushing for their wages to be lowered.
But experience shows that, in reality, immigrants are rather complementary than substitutes for national workers and are mainly engaged in professions in sectors with a lack of employment.
The low-skilled immigrants work in sectors that do not attract national workers and the more skilled in dynamic sectors where training does not meet the demand for personnel.
A positive effect on wages
In the same way that a surgeon would have difficulties working in a country that has a lack of anesthetists, the complementarity between nationals and immigrants causes the arrival of the latter to positively influence the salaries and employment of nationals.
Taking the above into account, Giovanni Peri calculated that a 1% increase in migratory flows implies a long-term rise in real wages of between 0.6 and 0.9%.
And, regardless of the fact that the diversity brought by immigrants contributes to the creation of ideas and economic growth (there is a large proportion of naturalized American Nobel laureates and companies such as Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
Immigrants are also net contributors to social systems, contributing on average 1% of the total budget in European countries.
The International Labor Organization estimates, for example, that in Germany an immigrant arriving at the age of 30 will make a net contribution (income minus expenses) of 150,000 euros to public budgets on average throughout his life.
At the beginning of his term, Nicolas Sarkozy wanted to go find his missing growth points &quot;with his teeth.&quot;
Such teeth, which deterred immigrants, had exactly the reverse effect.
Europe invented democracy, it only needs to think of a European democracy
Democracy is a precious commodity, but it is also a fragile one.
The European continent should be able to remember it since, although it was invented in Athens more than two thousand years ago, throughout the 20th century it has suffered the tragedies of the World War, totalitarianism, the Holocaust, the gulag, but also Franco in Spain, Salazar in Portugal, the colonels in Greece.
Some perhaps believed that, for democracy to finally triumph over its enemies, it would be enough to exercise the vote and in the most direct way possible.
We know, since Napoleon &quot;the Little&quot;, that it was something thought.
Universal suffrage, although it is a necessary condition for democracy, is not sufficient by itself and can even become an &quot;instrument of oppression&quot;, as the republican philosopher Etienne Vacherot used to say.
No, democracy requires much more: a public space, a public spirit, values, an organization, a separation and control of powers, an education, Enlightenment, economic and social solidarity, justice.
The crisis we are experiencing in Europe is an economic crisis, but it is about to become a political and democratic crisis.
The palinodia of the true-false Greek referendum had, in this regard, a double revealing effect: it showed the need for a powerful return to the political sphere, but also the worrying sense of its impossibility, of its incongruity.
This ambivalence must be reflected upon in order to overcome it.
The truth is that the front lines of the democratic battle currently have shifted and that, in many cases, Republican soldiers are no longer advancing in a good way.
We will not win if we demand a succession of national referendums, organized according to need and in a haphazard manner.
A blank signature to the absolute European monarch or a halt to the void of the nationalist hole: what options for the citizen!
No, we do not want to bring about blows, but rather a common, full-fledged, calm and continuous exercise of options and democracy, this time on a European scale.
There is no crisis in Greece, Italy, Spain, Portugal (in fact, we would not know where to end the list), because there is only one crisis, the crisis in Europe.
The whole of Europe is the one that bows to the orders of the markets and the rating agencies, that the one that suffers from its impotence and its lack of solidarity.
It is the whole of Europe that suffers humiliation in the international sphere.
We are concerned about the transfer of sovereignty to Europe, but it is the whole of Europe that is slowly losing sovereignty and, with it, each of its nations.
The most urgent thing is for popular sovereignty to regain the helm of the European project.
Because only together will Europeans be able to reduce the burden of their debts, free themselves from the markets and prepare their future through investments.
Exiting the crisis will require decisions at the European level that cannot be taken without full democratic legitimacy, unless it is to lead to disaster.
Having fought for a long time against this proposal by the Socialists and Jacques Delors, everyone is now calling for European economic governance.
So be it.
But to think about it without greater political and democratic integration, and without it being experienced as such by citizens, would be a new madness and would lead us to a new stalemate.
We must take on a new stage of European construction.
To build the Republic in France, it was necessary to &quot;make&quot; republicans.
The interest-motivated Revolution would not be enough.
This lesson still applies.
We must build a more economically integrated Europe.
It can only be achieved by building a more democratic Europe on the political level, a true European popular sovereignty.
To build Europe, let&#39;s make Europeans.
&quot;Contactless&quot; chip cards are becoming more widespread
The world chip card show kicks off on Tuesday in Villepinte, near Paris, with an optimistic atmosphere.
In fact, 2011 should end with an 11% increase in world sales of cards with microprocessors (bank cards, phones with SIM cards, etc.), with a total of 6,000 million units, according to calculations by the Eurosmart cabinet.
The most powerful segment is that of contactless technology, which makes it possible to pay for joint transport or purchases simply by bringing the card to a reader.
This year, 460 million contactless chip cards will be sold worldwide, 320 million more than the previous year!
Its share should continue to increase in 2012 (580 million units are expected) and represent around 10% of the world chip card market (6.925 million cards).
Europe, which has long lagged behind the Asia-Pacific region, is gaining ground in the contactless sector.
Around 26 million Visa bank cards already have this function, which is accepted at 75,000 payment terminals.
In France, its beginnings are more modest: 400,000 contactless Visa cards are being used.
But large stores work for four.
Carrefour has issued 2.5 million contactless Pass MasterCard cards this year.
To get into the upper gear, however, banks need to make them available to their customers.
&quot;There are two large French establishments that have committed to systematically disseminating in the future, among their customers, bank cards equipped with the contactless system&quot;, announces Gérard Nébouy, CEO of Visa Europe France.
Banks test mobile phone payment
But it is only a first step towards the payment method of the future: the mobile phone.
Currently, there are few devices equipped with NFC (Near Field Communication) technology, essential to carry out transactions.
&quot;They are lagging behind.&quot;
&quot;But it should finally see a real boom next year.&quot;
&quot;We anticipate that between 80 and 120 million units will be sold in 2012 worldwide,&quot; explains Marc Bertin, President of Eurosmart.
But the banks take the lead.
Credit agricole bank announced yesterday the launch of a test between December and next June in Caen.
The iPhones of around 200 customers and collaborators will be equipped with a case that allows contactless payment.
The BPCE has a similar project in Strasbourg and Marseille.
And the Société générale has also affirmed yesterday that it is preparing the commercialization of an offer that allows its customers to pay without contact through their mobile.
