The Nord Stream, the new gateway for Russian gas in Europe
The Nord Stream gas pipeline, which directly connects Western Europe with Russia via the bottom of the Baltic Sea, has already been put into service.
It must supply gas to meet the needs of thirty million homes.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate the event with great pomp.
Last Tuesday, more than 500 guests, including four Heads of State and Government, participated on the shores of the Baltic, between the music of the orchestra and a delicate buffet, in the inauguration of the Nord Stream, the new gas pipeline that communicates directly, under the sea, Russia with Germany.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitri Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his counterpart from the Netherlands, Mark Rutte, have together turned the handwheel of the valve that controls the entry of Russian gas into the network of Western Europe.
With this new gas pipeline, an additional 27.5 million cubic meters of Russian gas will reach Western Europe each year through a first stretch of 1,224 km that connects the Saint Petersburg region with the Land of Mecklenburg-Pomerania.
A second pipe should be completed by the end of 2012 which will allow a total of 55,000 million cubic meters of gas to be supplied, that is, enough to cover all French consumption.
In addition, there is already talk of the possibility of building a third tube along the same route.
For Gazprom, the completion of this enormous work on time presents an air of victory.
Poland and the Baltic countries had strongly opposed the project.
In fact, the Nord Stream will allow gas to be supplied directly to Germany, avoiding the overland route through third countries (Poland and Ukraine).
Suddenly, these two countries lose some of their power: it will be more difficult for them to influence Russia by threatening to cut off access to Western European markets.
At the height of the debate, Warsaw did not hesitate to compare the Nord Stream as a &quot;new German-Soviet pact&quot;, referring to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
That is, if the issue is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, supporting the Russian project, has obtained greater security of supply.
But the price is a weakening of the Europe of energy, since the project has created a gap between the Europeans of the east and the west.
Russia has managed, in just five years, to make successful its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and rich Western countries, big gas consumers and with increasingly limited reserves.
&quot;This gas pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, a new artery that unites us organically,&quot; confirmed François Fillon during the inauguration of the pipeline, demonstrating to what extent large contracts in the gas sector are as political as they are economic.
All this explains the wide smiles on the faces of Gazprom managers, numerous in Lubmin, at the gas arrival point.
The construction of this gas pipeline is also a technical achievement.
The submarine tube is made of cement-coated steel to protect it against ship anchors.
It rests on the bottom of the sea, at an average depth of 200 m.
To build it, it was necessary to avoid minefields dating back to World War II.
&quot;It was necessary to remove or destroy a hundred of them, as a precaution,&quot; says Jens Müller, spokesman for the Nord Stream society.
Likewise, it was necessary to take extreme measures to protect the fauna and flora.
The tube is a long metal snake that weighs about 242 Eiffel Towers and is not interrupted along its entire length: not by valves, not by maintenance stations.
A control platform was planned in the waters of Sweden, but those responsible for the project gave it up when they saw that the Swedes were not very willing to allow a Russian state company to establish itself permanently in the sea off their coast.
&quot;In the event of a breakdown, we will interrupt the gas flow in less than a minute,&quot; says Jens Müller.
In the event of a leak, the gas from the pipeline will therefore be released into the atmosphere.
But builders consider a leak unlikely, as they have predicted joints that are expected to leak every 100,000 years.
The control of the state of the gas pipeline is ensured by means of an underwater robot, towed by a ship, which performs external inspections, as well as by means of a device that circulates inside the gas pipeline.
Shaped like a cigar, it is inserted inside the tube, which has a diameter of one meter, and moves with the gas.
Upon arrival, after three full days of travel at a speed of three meters per second, it provides precise data on possible deformations of the metal.
The pipeline has been designed to operate for fifty years without the need for any type of repair.
The gas circulation is ensured simply by pressure.
At the beginning it is 200 bars and at the exit it is 100 bars.
Five companies have joined forces to carry out this project.
The leading company is Gazprom, which owns 51% of the shares.
It was joined by the German companies E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), as well as the Dutch Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies have created a joint company, called Nord Stream, in charge of building and operating the gas pipeline.
It is based in Zoug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favorable.
Afterwards, Gazprom leased to said company, for a renewable period of 25 years, the entire gas transmission capacity.
&quot;You will pay Gazprom for the full capacity, regardless of how much gas is actually transported,&quot; says Jens Müller.
The financing of the construction of the gas pipeline has been carried out in 30% with the contribution of the shareholders and in 70% through bank loans.
The total cost of the work should reach 7,400 million euros for the two tubes.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment has reached 240 million.
But minority shareholders are confident that they will not outgrow their investment, as Gazprom bears the expense risk alone.
The pipeline emerges from the Baltic at Lubmin, on a sandy shore planted with pine trees.
Valves, 4.5 meters high, form the gas outlet door.
There are sensors that measure the pressure, temperature and specific characteristics of the gas on arrival, before it is transferred to German pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, the terminal has received one million cubic meters of Russian gas every hour.
At full capacity, it will be three million per hour and in 2012, six million.
Moleskine, a brand notebook.
Created half a century ago by an Italian company, Moleskine wants to give people back their taste for writing.
It has an air of adventure, of hours of writing by candlelight.
The Moleskine notebook is easily recognizable, with its black rectangular pastes, its rubber, its off-white sheets, as if aged by time.
However, Moleskine notebooks with the current look were born ... in 1997.
The Italian company Modo Modo, based in Milan, decided at that time to launch a designer but distinguished notebook on the market.
Maria Sebregondi, at that time a consultant for the company, was in charge of the launch of the new product.
The notebook is inspired by an ancient production technique, mole skin, which refers to a varnished cotton that was used, among other things, to cover sidewalks.
This type of notebook was highly valued by writers and travelers.
&quot;Moleskine has adapted to current taste an old and forgotten object, an icon of avant-garde artists until the 20th century,&quot; says Maria Sebregondi, who has since become the head of the brand at Modo Modo.
And it was successful.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26%, reaching a volume of 12.7 million units sold.
Far has been the confidential production of the first years, in which only 3,000 notebooks were designed.
Moleskine goes beyond the Italian borders and exports its products to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It is difficult to determine the profile of the buyer, since the notebook attracts both businessmen and students and professionals.
Like Moleskine, its users are cosmopolitan, open-minded and cultured.
The small Italian company, which initially had twelve workers, now has about 100 and, since 2008, has two offices: one in Milan and the other in New York.
He distributes his notebooks in bookstores, from the Fnac to the small shops in the center of cities, and has been able to impose his identity.
&quot;We have adapted to the times and the need to write, despite the boom in emails,&quot; explains Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural firm goes hand in hand with the development of Moleskine: recently, the brand has launched the exhibition &quot;Detour&quot; where architects or artists exhibit their own notebook.
In August, it also released a leopard-print notebook on the occasion of the Locarno Film Festival.
Taking advantage of its success and this cultural aura, Moleskine has been able to diversify its products: bags, diaries, pens, computer cases ... The brand covers a wide range of media.
A success that provokes envy: in autumn 2006, Modo Modo was acquired by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, now Syntegra Capital, thus writing a new page in the history of Moleskine.
Why is the unemployment rate for disabled workers still so high?
About 19% of disabled people are looking for a job.
The XV Week for the employment of the disabled starts today.
Despite a determined public policy, applied since 2005, the unemployment rate among disabled people is double the average rate: 19%, compared to 9% for the population as a whole.
Discouraging?
&quot;No,&quot; says Éric Blanchet, CEO of Adapt, the association that organizes the week for the employment of the disabled.
&quot;The progress made over the last 15 years is considerable.
&quot;Back then, the unemployment rate was not twice but three times higher than the average.
&quot;However, there is still a lot to do.&quot;
It is worth mentioning that the disabled unemployed continue to face numerous obstacles to accessing employment.
They tend to be older: 37% are over 50 years old (17% on average).
They have a low level of qualification: 80% have not finished high school and, of the 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10,000 are disabled.
Finally, long-term unemployment is very widespread among them: 53% for the disabled, compared to 38% on average.
In other words, there are many issues that make it particularly difficult to return to work and that &quot;are the crux of the problem,&quot; says Christian Grapin, CEO of Tremplin, an association created in 1992 to help companies hire disabled workers.
Those are the objective obstacles.
Also, there are those that are not mentioned; people&#39;s minds advance, but too slowly.
A study carried out in April by the IMS-Entreprendre association for the Cité pointed out that the surveyed directors have &quot;a low level of knowledge about disabilities&quot;, with an &quot;over-representation of people in wheelchairs, physically or intellectually handicapped.&quot;
The result: private companies with more than 20 workers are very far from the goal of hiring 6% disabled workers, a goal that was set in a law of ... 1987.
According to the latest available figures, dating from 2008, they reach a ratio of 2.6%.
&quot;Now we reach around 3%,&quot; says Pierre Blanc, general director of Agefiph, the body in charge of collecting contributions from companies that do not respect this law.
The proof: the number of establishments &quot;subject to this contribution&quot;, as well as the amounts disbursed, have decreased between 2007 and 2011, from 59,000 to 46,000 structures (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
&quot;The 2005 law, which increased contributions, has created great pressure for companies,&quot; explains Pierre Blanc.
&quot;But this improvement also reflects a real awareness, particularly among large groups.&quot;
According to the Ministry of Labor, only 59% of companies with between 20 and 49 workers have disabled employees in their workforce, compared to 82% of companies with between 100 and 199 workers.
